# Output marking convention (all agent prompts)

Use this **exactly** so humans and orchestrators can scan results quickly.

## Status tokens (per verification line)

| Meaning                  | Token | When to use                                                                                                                                           |
| --- | ----- | ----- |
| **Verified / passing**   | `[✓]` | Criterion satisfied for the given scope (cite evidence: file, hunk, or behavior).                                                                     |
| **Not satisfied / risk** | `[x]` | Criterion **not** met or cannot be verified from provided inputs. **Required:** add **Recommendation** and, if possible, a **Code suggestion** block. |

> **Note on `[]` vs `[x]`:** Some teams phrase “unchecked template” as `[ ]`. Here **`[x]` always means failure / not satisfied**, not “completed checkbox”. **`[✓]` means verified OK** (use `[PASS]` instead of `[✓]` if you need strict ASCII).
> | **Not applicable** | `[~]` | Criterion does not apply to this scope (say why in one short phrase). |
> | **Blocked** | `[?]` | Cannot verify (missing diff, missing ticket, wrong branch, etc.); say what is missing. |

## Required shape after each `[x]`

````text
[x] <criterion one-liner>
    Recommendation: <concrete next step>
    Code suggestion (optional):
    ```ts
    // minimal illustrative fix or pattern
    ```
````

## Scope discipline

- **PR review agents:** only judge **changed** files/hunks vs `origin/release...HEAD` unless the prompt says otherwise.
- **Implementation agents:** judge **new/edited** work for the ticket, plus commands the prompt authorizes.

Do **not** mix “PR review (no CI)” constraints from `review-pr` into implementation verification prompts that require `pnpm ci:test`, unless the orchestrator explicitly combines them.
